  <main id="main">
    <h1 id="title">Dr. Kamala Sohonie</h1>
    <p class="tagline">India's First Lady of Science</p>

    <div id="img-div"> 
      <img id="image" src="https://tse3.mm.bing.net/th?id=OIP.TH5cFKFElsmEI0guIHYw0QHaIv&pid=Api"alt="Dr. Kamala Sohonie">
      <figcaption id="img-caption">
        Dr. Kamala Sohonie – India's first woman to earn a Ph.D. in science.
      </figcaption>
    </div>

    <section id="tribute-info">
      <p><strong>Full Name:</strong> Kamala Sohonie</p>
      <p><strong>Born:</strong> June 1912, Indore, Madhya Pradesh</p>
      <p><strong>Died:</strong> 1998, Mumbai, Maharashtra</p>
      <p><strong>Field:</strong> Biochemistry</p>
      <p><strong>Known For:</strong> First Indian woman to earn a Ph.D. in a scientific field</p>
      <p><strong>Ph.D.:</strong> University of Cambridge</p>
      <p><strong>Key Contributions:</strong> Nutrition research, especially Neera</p>

      <h3>🌱 Early Life & Education</h3>
      <p>Kamala was born into a scientific family. Her father and uncle were chemists who graduated from IISc. She graduated with top honors in Chemistry from Bombay University in 1933.</p>

      <h3>🚪 Struggle for Acceptance in Science</h3>
      <p>Initially rejected by Sir C.V. Raman at IISc, Kamala protested. He accepted her under strict conditions. She proved herself through dedication and excellence, eventually earning his praise.</p>

      <h3>🎓 Ph.D. at Cambridge</h3>
      <p>She completed her Ph.D. in 14 months. Her research focused on enzymes, vitamins, and proteins.</p>

      <h3>🍃 Scientific Contributions</h3>
      <p><strong>🧴 Research on Neera:</strong> She discovered it was rich in Vitamin C, useful for malnourished children and pregnant women.</p>
      <p><strong>🧬 Other Work:</strong> Contributed to India's understanding of protein deficiency and nutrition through roles at Coonoor and Bombay.</p>

      <h3>🧠 Legacy and Impact</h3>
      <p>Kamala paved the way for women in Indian science. She mentored future scientists and shaped nutrition policy in India.</p>

      <h3>👏 Awards and Recognition</h3>
      <p>Though not widely honored during her life, she is now remembered as a pioneer who broke barriers in STEM fields.</p>

      <blockquote>💬 "I had to prove not only my own worth, but the worth of all women who would come after me."</blockquote>

      <h3>🎯 Why She’s Still Relevant</h3>
      <p>Her life stands as a symbol of resilience and empowerment in today's ongoing fight for gender equality in STEM.</p>
    </section>

